{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12314"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12314"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.71,0.02,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4835"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9042"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of pain in his right eye. The pain is mild in intensity and is associated with the sensation of a foreign body, watery eyes, photophobia and decreased vision. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His visual acuity is 6/12 in the right eye, and 6/6 in the left eye. There is ciliary congestion present with decreased corneal sensation, and corneal staining with 2% fluorescein shows an epithelial defect linear in appearance with multiple other linear epithelial defects branching off from the same point.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical gentamicin","Topical natamycin","Topical acyclovir","Oral fluconazole","Topical voriconazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of herpes simplex keratitis. The characteristic findings include a dendritic (branching) ulcer on fluorescein staining, decreased corneal sensation, pain, photophobia, and reduced visual acuity. Herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1) is the most common cause of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for herpes simplex keratitis. It is an antiviral medication that inhibits viral DNA synthesis. The typical regimen is acyclovir 3% ointment applied five times daily until the ulcer heals, followed by a tapering regimen. Early treatment is essential to prevent deeper corneal involvement and potential scarring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E is an aminoglycoside antibiotic used for bacterial keratitis. Bacterial keratitis typically presents with a more suppurative (pus-forming) ulcer, often with a grey-white infiltrate. Unlike herpetic keratitis, bacterial keratitis usually follows trauma, contact lens wear, or occurs in patients with ocular surface disease. The dendritic pattern seen in this patient is not characteristic of bacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical natamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal agent used primarily for filamentous fungal keratitis. Fungal keratitis typically has a more indolent course with a feathery or fluffy-appearing infiltrate. It is often associated with vegetative trauma or agricultural work. The dendritic pattern and decreased corneal sensation in this patient are not consistent with fungal keratitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical voriconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is another antifungal agent used for fungal keratitis, particularly for Candida and Aspergillus species. It may also be used in cases of Acanthamoeba keratitis, which typically presents with severe pain disproportionate to clinical findings and often a ring-shaped infiltrate. Neither of these conditions presents with the dendritic pattern seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is a systemic antifungal medication used for severe fungal infections. It would not be effective against herpes simplex virus and is not indicated for viral keratitis. Systemic antifungals are typically reserved for severe fungal keratitis with deep stromal involvement or when there is risk of intraocular spread.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes simplex keratitis is characterised by dendritic ulcers and decreased corneal sensation.","Topical acyclovir is the first-line treatment for herpes simplex keratitis.","Dendritic ulcers have a branching pattern with terminal bulbs that stain with fluorescein."],"references":["Ahmad B, Gurnani B, Patel BC. Herpes Simplex Keratitis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2024 Mar 10. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31424862/","Kaye S, Choudhary A. Herpes simplex keratitis. Prog Retin Eye Res. 2006 Jul;25(4):355-80. doi: 10.1016/j.preteyeres.2006.05.001. Epub 2006 Jun 27. PMID: 16807055. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16807055/","Musa M, Enaholo E, Aluyi-Osa G, Atuanya GN, Spadea L, Salati C, Zeppieri M. Herpes simplex keratitis: A brief clinical overview. World J Virol. 2024 Mar 25;13(1):89934. doi: 10.5501/wjv.v13.i1.89934. PMID: 38616855; PMCID: PMC11008405. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11008405/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12314"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73443"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-08T20:57:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-08T20:58:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4835"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89263"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"he